.TH TFCTL-FILTERS 7 "2025-09-25" "tfctl" "Miscellaneous Information"
.SH NAME
tfctl-filters \- filtering expressions with tfctl
.SH SYNOPSIS
Use the
.BR \-\-filter
flag to narrow results.
.SH DESCRIPTION
Filters are comma\-delimited by default and have the form
.IR key<op>target .
Negation is written by prefixing the operator with
.B !
(e.g.,
.IR name!@prod ).
.SH OPERATORS
.TP
.B =
Exact match (string equality).
.TP
.B ~
Case\-insensitive equality.
.TP
.B ^
Starts with.
.TP
.B > , <
Lexicographic comparisons.
.TP
.B @
Contains / membership (strings, slices, maps).
.TP
.B /
Regular expression match (Go regexp syntax).
.SH NOTES
- Filters referencing attribute names beginning with
.B _
are treated as native API filters and may be passed through upstream.
- Filters are applied before attribute transformations.
- For
.B sq
with
.BR \-\-concrete ,
.B mode=managed
is automatically appended.
.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
# Contains and negation
tfctl oq --filter 'name@prod'
tfctl oq --filter 'name!@prod'

# Exact, starts\-with, case\-insensitive
tfctl wq --filter 'status=applied'
tfctl wq --filter 'name^prod'
tfctl oq --filter 'email~admin'

# Regex
tfctl wq --filter 'name/^prod-\d{3}$'

# Multiple filters
tfctl oq --filter 'name@prod,created-at>2024-01-01'
.fi
